Sat Mar  9 08:31:25 UTC 2002  Aaron Krowne <akrowne@vt.edu> Note 0025

  1. Got the query spellfixer up and running.  It takes the form of a daemon
     which is in the bin directory, called "spelld".  It basically just sits
     there and listens for requests on TCP port 3060 (changable in the config)
     for some input.  When a client connects and prints a sentence (which is
     meant to be a query), it splits the query up and looks for all of the
     words in the lexicon.  This is done using n-gram indexing, approximated
     Ukkonen distance, and finally Levenshtein distance as a fine-grained 
     comparison metric.  The daemon then returns a sentence which contains one
     word for each input word.  The results are "+" for a word in the lexicon,
     "-" for a word not in the lexicon and which couldn't be corrected, and
     a replacement word for words not in the lexicon which corrections were
     found for.  In Search.pm is a fixQuery() sub which acts as a client that
     sends a query to this daemon, and parses the output into a replacement 
     query.  If any "-" words result, it gives up.  Much more work needs to be 
     done; for instance, the spell daemon should probably output a "-" if its 
     suggestion ends up having a Levenshtein distance which is above some 
     threshold. 
  
  2. Found and fixed a bug in the search engine whereby a divide by zero would
     occur for queries on words which exist in the index, but do not occur 
     in any documents.  Also synched the query df weighting with the method
     of weighting based on df for the document vectors.

Fri Mar  8 01:27:46 UTC 2002  Aaron Krowne <akrowne@vt.edu> Note 0024

