     httpd.conf (stole this notion from scoop).  This file should be copied
     into lib/httpd-planetmath.conf, and included from there.  The file in
     etc is stored in cvs and serves as an example or starting point.  The
     file in lib is what is installation specific, and should be what is
     included into httpd.conf.


Wed Mar  6 20:07:50 UTC 2002  Aaron Krowne <akrowne@vt.edu> Note 0021

  1. Augmented the orphaning system slightly so it can recognize who the last
     owner of an object was, and avoid updating the grace interval when this
     same person adopts back their own object.  This is done by changing the 
     owner of an object to -(oldid), where oldid is the user id of the owner,
     at abandoning time.  All comparisons have been updated so that userid<=0
     is the true "unowned" criterion.  To check if we should update the grace
     interval at adoption time, we simply check if $curuserid=-$userid.  NOTE:
     We should probably change the "anonymous" user to be user zero everywhere
     in the code.  Currently, we have a user with id 1, and there could be some
     conflicts as -1 is the "nobody" user right now.

  2. Added an autoOrphan function and a call to it in the outstandingcor 
     script.  Now orphaning should happen automatically.


Mon Mar  4 05:15:39 UTC 2002  Logan Hanks <logan@vt.edu> Note 0020

  1. Made some minor additions to the (so far) undocumented orphanage and
     adoption system.

    a) Added function isAdoptable, to make the logic buried in the orphanage
       function accessible.

    b) Changed the adoptObject function so that it checks isAdoptable.  The
       implementation was that an object was only adoptable if it was
       unowned, but this contradicted the orphanage function, so I presumed
       the logic that is now in isAdoptable is acceptable to govern this.

    c) Implemented reset of graceint on pending corrections for an object
       when it is adopted (as described in Note 0019-3).

    d) Also added a check that prevents adopting objects you already own.
       However, nothing prevents you from abandoning and then adopting
       your own objects, so one can avoid responding to corrections
       indefinitely by this method (not sure if it's worth the trouble to
       prevent).

    e) Fixed logchange.pl (there are exactly 9 days a month where the day of
       the month has a single digit, you know :P).


Sun Mar  3 10:47:19 UTC 2002  Aaron Krowne <akrowne@vt.edu> Note 0019

  1. (These changes are really all from yesterday) Implemented + and - (which
     I call "forcing" and "forbidding") functionality to the search engine.  
     This allows the user to require that a word appear in the "match set" for
     and entry, or allows the user to require that a word NOT appear.  The
     functionality appears to work completely. 

  2. Added a "self" field to the encyclopedia objects table. This should be set
     to "true" if the object contains its own proof.  Added code to the "show
     unproven theorems" functionality to check for this flag.  Added a control
     to the admin metadata editor to turn this flag on.  Added functionality
     to the update object metadata functions to handle checkboxes as booleans.
     Still need to add this to the normal object editor screen.

  3. Added an outstanding correction nag system.  Added a "nag_times" hash to
     the config describing when the various nag stages happen and how the 
     nagging recurs.  Added the "nag" table, which allows the system to 
     remember the time of last nag.  Added an outstandingcor script to the bin
     directory, which gets run every hour to process nags (and soon, orphaning
     objects automatically.)  Most of the nag functions are in Corrections.pm.
     Also added a "graceint" field to the corrections table.  This is a "grace
     interval", which is meant to be used if an object is adopted.  At such 
     time, it should be set to the difference between the current time and the
     time each correction was filed, so that the new owner may "start fresh".

Sat Mar  2 23:29:37 UTC 2002  Logan Hanks <logan@vt.edu> Note 0018

  1. Implemented the beginnings of a pronunciation guide system.  See
     Pronounce.pm.  Any pronunciation has associated with it an encoding.
     An encoding merely consists of a method to render it to html so that
     it has a human readable form.  In the future it will also be possible
     to denote mappings between encodings, so that, for instance, something
     simple like "jargon" encoding could be automatically translated to
     "IPA".


