     This parameter only has effect for admins and, if defined lists all
     objects with pending corrects (as opposed to the list of all
     corrections for the current user that it typically displays).


Mon Feb 25 14:22:49 UTC 2002  Aaron Krowne <akrowne@vt.edu> Note 0004

  1. Changed $MATH_SCALE_FACTOR back to 1.6.  There were some occurances of
     very ugly rendering with the smaller scale factor.  If you dont believe
     me, try setting the scale factor back to 1.5 and rerendering the 
     "self-dual" entry.  Look at the \rightarrows and equal signs in 
     particular, parts of them nearly dissapear.  Other symbols are bad too.

  2. Completely changed the synonym handling system and generalized it to 
     handle a "defines" field.  This involved:

     * Creating a new table, objindex, which serves as a "title" index for
       any object on planetmath.  This includes defines, synonyms, and 
       actual "master" titles for an entry.  The different types are 
       differentiated by 1 for master, 2 for synonym, and 3 for defines.

     * Changing the encyclopedia index to query the above table instead of
       the encyclopedia table (objects) itself. 

     * Changing createSynonyms and deleteSynonyms to use the new schema.

     * Changing getEncyclopediaExtras to display "defines" if there are any.

     * Changing the encyclopedia entry "add" and edit forms for handling 
       the "defines" field, as well as the support functions for these forms.

     * Creating an "indexTitle" in Indexing.pm which maintains the objindex
       record for the title for an object, and calling this from object 
       adding/updating locations (in Encyclopedia.pm and EditObj.pm.)

     Synonym/defines "surrogates" are still stored with each object's record,
     in "defines" and "synonym" fields.

  3. Updated the reference linking system to make use of the "defines" field.
     I thought this was going to be simple, but I ran into a little crisis at
     what should have been 3/4 of the way through implementing it.  The problem
     was that the mapping of a unique "concept" to an actual entry, and making
     sure that a link to that "concept" doesn't happen twice in the same entry,
     and that the first occurance of the "concept" is the only one that gets 
     linked, was going to be basically impossible the way things were done 
     before.  To fix this, I had to actually change the generateterms() 
     function to generate what I call a "concept id" for entries that are 
     truly unique concepts, and put them in a hash so that the object ids they
     refer to can be looked up.  So basically, the deciding factor for whether
     a term gets a new concept id is whether its type is either 1 (master 
     title entry) or 3 (defines entry.)  A concept id => object id hash is 
     built from these entries first, and then a reverse-lookup is done for all
     the synonyms and they are given concept ids that have already been
     generated.  

     The rest of the changes are in makelinks(), where unique "concepts" are 
     the final determining factor for whether a link is "unique."

     Note: There is a problem on the horizon.  We're going to have to take 
     care of the situation where someone needs to define synonyms for a 
     *defines* item in an object.  I guess we need an "advanced" synonyms 
     field where the user can enter things like
      
                defines1 = defines1.synonym1
                defines1 = defines1.synonym2
                defines2 = defines1.synonym2
                  ...    =      ...
                
     and then toss these mappings into objlinks as syonym types.
     
     Note: Much linking may be broken at this point, but I tried a couple 
     entries and they seem fine.

     Note: Why does vim syntax highlight "may" in changelogs??
     [jan feb mar... -LBH]

